[It may be assumed that similar preventive steps are being undertaken by other southern European countries.

Since its re-emergence in northern Greece in early April 2016, LSD has been spreading north and westward, with incursion in 5 countries. Despite the mitigation effect of the emergency vaccination campaign ongoing in the affected countries, uncontrolled animal movements and current weather conditions suitable for vector populations may be increasing the risk of spread. This is also apparent from a recent follow-up report from Serbia, submitted Thu 28 Jul 2016, notifying 27 new outbreaks, 7 of which were in the west, adjacent to the border with Montenegro. This follow-up report no. 7, with details on each of the new outbreaks and an interactive map, is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=20597.

Italy experienced, in 1993, economic losses exceeding 100 million Euro, when another highly infectious disease, namely FMD [foot-and-mouth disease], was introduced by cattle imported in 2 consignments, by land and by sea, accompanied by Croatian veterinary certificates (the Croatian authorities later claimed these certificates were forged). The virus was identified as a Middle Eastern strain of FMDV O1. The losses were mainly due to the imposed export restrictions. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4381042,75.]
